  <div class="article-header">
    <div class="tags">
      <span class="tag" style="background:#FAC775;color:#412402;">Reaction of the week</span>
      <span class="tag" style="background:#E1F5EE;color:#085041;">Oscillating Reaction</span>
      <span class="tag" style="background:#EEEDFE;color:#26215C;">High School</span>
    </div>
    <h1 class="article-title">The Briggs-Rauscher Reaction: A Chemical Traffic Light</h1>
    <p class="article-desc">Discover the mesmerizing oscillating reaction that cycles through amber, blue, and clear colors in a rhythmic dance of chemistry.</p>
    <div class="meta">8 min read · Includes video · 3 research links</div>
  </div>

  <div class="video-wrapper">
    <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/LL3kVtc-4vY" title="Briggs-Rauscher Oscillating Reaction" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
  </div>

  <div class="section-label">The reaction</div>
  <div class="equation-box">
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#AFA9EC;">IO₃⁻ + 2H₂O₂ + CH₂(COOH)₂ + H⁺</span>
    <span class="eq-arrow">→</span>
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#9FE1CB;">ICH(COOH)₂ + 2O₂ + 3H₂O</span>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">The Briggs-Rauscher reaction is one of the most spectacular demonstrations in chemistry, often called the "chemical traffic light" because of its stunning color changes. Named after its discoverers Thomas Briggs and Warren Rauscher in 1972, this oscillating reaction cycles rhythmically between colorless, amber, and deep blue states, creating a hypnotic display that can continue for several minutes.</p>
  <p class="body-text">What makes this reaction truly remarkable is its predictable oscillations. Unlike most chemical reactions that proceed steadily from reactants to products, the Briggs-Rauscher reaction alternates between different chemical states in a periodic fashion. The solution will be colorless for about 10 seconds, then suddenly turn amber, followed by a dramatic shift to deep blue, before returning to colorless again.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-title">What Causes the Color Changes?</div>
    <div class="callout-text">The color changes are caused by the periodic formation and consumption of iodine (I₂) and starch-iodine complexes. The amber color comes from iodine molecules, while the blue color results from the famous starch-iodine complex. When these compounds are consumed, the solution returns to colorless.</div>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">The reaction involves three main components: potassium iodate (KIO₃), hydrogen peroxide (H₂O₂), and malonic acid (CH₂(COOH)₂), along with sulfuric acid and starch as indicators. The magic happens through a complex mechanism involving two competing pathways - a radical pathway and a non-radical pathway - that alternate dominance, creating the oscillations. This reaction belongs to a class called "chemical oscillators" and demonstrates principles of non-linear dynamics and chaos theory in action.</p>

